comments.message:
I think we need to do a bit more here:

```
struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_attr_info {
    uint16_t size;
    uint32_t crc32;
};

struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_resp {
    size_t version;
    uint8_t completion_code;
    uint8_t handle;
    uint8_t option;
    uint8_t length;
    union {
        struct pldm_oem_file_io_read_attr_info attr;
    };
#ifndef __cplusplus
    uint8_t data[] LIBPLDM_CC_COUNTED_BY(length);
#endif
};
```

How this is used by the caller is to do:

```
struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_resp resp;

resp.version = sizeof(struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_resp);
...
```

This is a trick borrowed from the kernel:

[Conventions for extensible system calls](https://lwn.net/Articles/830666/)

It allows you to add further read options later while still providing backwards-compatibility.

I'll leave some further comments in the implementation.

Thank you for your suggestion. I understand the benefits of adding a new version field.
However, the data returned in struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_resp may be attributes or file data. 
Would it be better to change it to the following example ?

```c
struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_resp { 
     size_t version;
     uint8_t completion_code;
     uint8_t handle;
     uint8_t option;
     uint8_t length;
     union {
         struct pldm_oem_file_io_read_attr_info attr;
         struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_data_info info;
     };
#ifndef __cplusplus
     uint8_t data[] LIBPLDM_CC_COUNTED_BY(length);
#endif
};
```

You _must_ also include a parameter for the length of the object pointed to by `resp` since it contains a flexible array member.

With that you also need to add the following check:

```
if (resp_len < sizeof(*resp)) {
    return -EINVAL;
}
```

So regarding the extensible struct idea I suggested in the header, here we add:

```
if (resp->version > sizeof(*resp)) {
    return -E2BIG;
}
```

and then use `info` for the union member name just like on line 72 above? So:

```
union {
    struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_attr_info attr;
    struct pldm_oem_meta_file_io_read_data_info data;
} info;
```

Based on the comment on line 187 I think this can rather be:

```
switch (resp->option) {
case PLDM_OEM_META_FILE_IO_READ_ATTR:
case PLDM_OEM_META_FILE_IO_READ_DATA:
    break;
default:
    return -EPROTO;
}
```

We need to validate that we have a option value that we understand, but that should be all.
